[2] COVID19 associated mortality in ICU patients
Date: Mon 1 Feb 2021
Source: Anaesthesia [edited]
https://doi.org/10.1111/anae.15425


ref: Armstrong RA, Kane AD, Kursumovic E, et al. Mortality in patients admitted to intensive care with COVID-19: an updated systematic review and meta-analysis of observational studies. Anaesthesia. 2021 Feb 1. doi: 10.1111/anae.15425. Epub ahead of print. PMID: 33525063.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The COVID-19 pandemic continues to cause critical illness and deaths internationally. Up to 31 May 2020, mortality in patients admitted to intensive care units (ICU) with COVID-19 was 41.6%. Since then, changes in therapeutics and management may have improved outcomes. Also, data from countries affected later in the pandemic are now available. We searched MEDLINE, Embase, PubMed and Cochrane databases up to 30 Sep 2020 for studies reporting ICU mortality among adult patients with COVID-19 and present an updated systematic review and meta-analysis. The primary outcome measure was death in intensive care as a proportion of completed ICU admissions, either through discharge from intensive care or death. We identified 52 observational studies including 43 128 patients, and 1st reports from the Middle East, South Asia, and Australasia, as well as 4 national or regional registries. Reported mortality was lower in registries compared with other reports. In two regions, mortality differed significantly from all others, being higher in the Middle East and lower in a single registry study from Australasia. Although ICU mortality (95% CI) was lower than reported in June (35.5% (31.3-39.9%) vs. 41.6% (34.0-49.7%)), the absence of patient level data prevents a definitive evaluation. A lack of standardisation of reporting prevents comparison of cohorts in terms of underlying risk, severity of illness or outcomes. We found that the decrease in ICU mortality from COVID-19 has reduced or plateaued since May 2020 and note the possibility of some geographical variation. More standardisation in reporting would improve the ability to compare outcomes from different reports.

--
communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The management of critically ill patients with COVID-19 infection has been updated with multiple experimental therapies introduced at various times. Most therapeutic agents have shown limited or equivocal impact except dexamethasone and monoclonal antibodies. Data are evolving describing outcomes from COVID-19 in critically ill patients who develop acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) (1). Mortality appears lower than that in patients with severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS-CoV) or Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS). The mortality from COVID-19 appears driven by the presence of severe ARDS, and ranges widely, from 12 to 78 per cent with an average of 25 to 50 per cent (https://www.uptodate.com/contents/coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-critical-care-and-airway-management-issues).

Mortality may be decreasing as the pandemic progresses; In an analysis of patients during a resurgence of COVID-19 in Houston, Texas, in-hospital mortality was lower during the 2nd surge compared to the 1st surge (5 versus 12 per cent) but the difference in ICU mortality was not significant (23 versus 28 per cent) (2). In another French cohort of over 4000 critically-ill patients, mortality also decreased from 42 to 25 per cent over a 4-month period during the pandemic (3). In a United States analysis of 468 patients with COVID-19-related critical illness from 1 Mar 2020 to 11 May 2020, the mortality decreased from 44 to 19 per cent (4). The observed reduction in mortality could be reflective of many factors; a patient population that is younger and has a lower comorbidity burden during the 2nd surge, reduced burden of institutions, and/or growing expertise with COVID-19 care and management.]

References
----------
1. Murthy S, Gomersall CD, Fowler RA. Care for critically ill patients with COVID-19. JAMA. 2020 Apr 21;323(15):1499-1500. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.3633. PMID: 32159735; https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2762996.
2. Vahidy FS, Drews AL, Masud FN, et al. Characteristics and outcomes of COVID-19 patients during initial peak and resurgence in the Houston Metropolitan Area. JAMA. 2020 Sep 8; 324(10): 998-1000. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.15301. PMID: 32789492; PMCID: PMC7426882.
3. COVID-ICU Group on behalf of the REVA Network and the COVID-ICU Investigators. Clinical characteristics and day-90 outcomes of 4244 critically ill adults with COVID-19: a prospective cohort study. Intensive Care Med. 2021 Jan; 47(1): 60-73. doi: 10.1007/s00134-020-06294-x. Epub 2020 Oct 29. PMID: 33211135; PMCID: PMC7674575; https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00134-020-06294-x.
4. Anesi GL, Jablonski J, Harhay MO, et al. Characteristics, outcomes, and trends of patients with COVID-19-related critical illness at a learning health system in the United States. Ann Intern Med. 2021 Jan 19. doi: 10.7326/M20-5327. Epub ahead of print. PMID: 33460330; https://www.acpjournals.org/doi/10.7326/M20-5327.
- Mod.UBA]

